In article <2l1mipINN72l@fstgds15.tu-graz.ac.at> vristic@iaik.wu-wien.ac.at (Vesna Ristic) writes:
>>Suppose x is an integer, the "multiplicative inverse of x modulo m" is an
>>integer y such that
>>
>>        xy [congruent] 1 (mod m)        (in the mathematician's notation)
>>
>>or equivalently,
>>
>>        xy mod m = 1                    (in the computer scientist's notation)
>
>In fact, congruence is *stronger* than mod:
>...

By "equivalently", I meant that the two conditions are equivalent
semantically.  But I didn't mean to imply

	a [congruent] b (mod m)
	
is in general equivalent to

	a mod m = b

-- Nicol
